Accept and @type are two separate concerns.

@type hints the client at what type(s) the link might be. This lets the UA
decides if it can process teh link or not.

Accept: tells the server which formats it can process.

If a UA can&#39;t understand the @type, it probably can&#39;t process it and may
ignore it. If it can, and it issues an Accept header, then surely that type
will be in the Accept header anyway.

If you want to distinctly identify two documents separately, you give them
two URIs. If the difference between the two representations don&#39;t matter to
the client (aka there is no significant semantic difference between the two
formats), then two representations can be served as conneg&#39;d resources.

Seb

